Upgrading Eggdrop

  It is easy to upgrade Eggdrop to a new version! To have a full picture
  of the changes made since your last upgrade, we recommend reading the
  NEWS file. Upgrades from the 1.8 and 1.9 lines of Eggdrop should take
  place with little to no issues. While the config file, user files, and
  channel files can all be reused, it is recommended to review the NEWS
  files for each release to identify new configuration settings that
  have been added.

  For support, feel free to visit us on Libera #eggdrop.

HOW TO UPGRADE

  To upgrade to a newer version of Eggdrop, first backup your config
  file, user file, and chan file. While they are saved and should not
  be overwritten by the upgrade process, it never hurts to make another
  copy :)

  Next, view the NEWS file to see what changes have been made, paying
  particular attention to the config file section to see what
  new/different settings have been added. Update your config file
  appropriately.

  Then, simply follow the same steps you followed to install Eggdrop
  previously. Build with Meson + Ninja (see INSTALL for details) and
  install. Restart your Eggdrop and you will be up and running with the
  latest version.

MIGRATING FROM .CONF (Tcl) TO .TOML (TOML FORMAT)

  This fork introduces a modern TOML configuration format. Your existing
  .conf files continue to work unchanged — migration is entirely optional.

  Why migrate?
    - No Tcl knowledge required to configure the bot
    - Cleaner, human-readable syntax: key = "value"
    - Organised sections: [bot], [servers], [channels], [modules], ...
    - No 'chmod u+x' or shebang (#!) line needed
    - Interactive setup wizard for new installs: eggdrop --setup

  METHOD 1 — Automated migration script (recommended):

      python3 scripts/conf2toml.py mybot.conf mybot.toml

    The script reads your existing .conf, converts all 'set' commands,
    server / channel / module / logfile directives, and source / unbind
    calls to their TOML equivalents. Review the output before using it.

  METHOD 2 — Start fresh with the setup wizard:

      eggdrop --setup mybot.toml

    Answer the prompts to generate a new config. Then manually transfer
    any custom settings from your old .conf that the wizard didn't cover.

  METHOD 3 — Manual conversion reference:

    Old .conf (Tcl)                  New .toml (TOML)
    ────────────────────────────     ────────────────────────────────────
    set nick "MyBot"                 [bot]
    set altnick "MyBot0"             nick    = "MyBot"
    set owner "MyNick"               altnick = "MyBot0"
                                     owner   = "MyNick"

    server add irc.net +6697         [servers]
                                     list = ["irc.net:+6697"]

    channel add #mychan              [channels]
                                     list = ["#mychan"]

    loadmodule server                [modules]
    loadmodule irc                   load = ["server", "irc", ...]

    logfile mco * eggdrop.log        [logging]
                                     entries = ["mco * eggdrop.log"]

    source scripts/foo.tcl           [scripts]
                                     load = ["scripts/foo.tcl"]

    unbind dcc n simul *dcc:simul    [tcl]
                                     commands = ["unbind dcc n simul *dcc:simul"]

  Variable name mapping: underscores in TOML map to dashes in eggdrop.
    botnet_nick  →  botnet-nick
    help_path    →  help-path
    max_logs     →  max-logs

  After migration, start the bot with the new file:

      eggdrop -m mybot.toml    # first run: creates user file
      eggdrop mybot.toml       # subsequent runs

MUST-READ CHANGES FOR EGGDROP V1.10 (devinkbrown fork)

These are NOT all the changes or new settings; rather just the "killer"
changes that may directly affect Eggdrop's previous performance without
modification.

Build system

  This fork uses Meson + Ninja instead of the upstream autoconf/make.
  See the INSTALL file for complete build instructions. The old
  './configure && make' workflow no longer exists in this fork.

Config file changes (devinkbrown fork)

-   TOML is now the default configuration format. The default config
    file name changed from 'eggdrop.conf' to 'eggdrop.toml'. Existing
    .conf files are fully supported; pass one explicitly on the command
    line: eggdrop mybot.conf

-   New 'eggdrop --setup' flag (also -s): interactive configuration
    wizard. Generates a ready-to-use eggdrop.toml. Replaces the need
    to manually edit the config file and add a shebang or chmod.

-   The 'chmod u+x' / shebang (#!) mechanism for running the config
    as a shell script is no longer required or recommended when using
    the TOML format.

Config file changes (upstream v1.10)

-   Eggdrop has deprecated the blowfish module for password hashing in
    favor of the PBKDF2 module. This is a BIG change which, if done
    carelessly, has the potential to render stored passwords useless.
    Please see doc/PBKDF2 for information on how to properly migrate
    your userfiles and passwords to the new module.

-   Eggdrop 1.9 switched from the "set servers {}" syntax to the "server
    add" command. For example, if your configuration file previously had:

        set servers {
          my.server.com:6667
        }

    you should now instead use (in .conf):

        server add my.server.com 6667

    or (in .toml):

        [servers]
        list = ["my.server.com:6667"]

-   Eggdrop no longer requires the '-n' flag to start Eggdrop in
    terminal mode.

Modules

While most 3rd party modules that worked on older Eggdrop versions
should still work with Eggdrop, many of them contain a version check
that only allows them to run on 1.6.x bots. We have removed the version
check from some of the more popular modules; find them at:
https://ftp.eggheads.org/pub/eggdrop/modules/1.10/

Scripts

All 3rd party Tcl scripts that worked with Eggdrop versions as early as
v1.6 should still fully work with Eggdrop.

Botnet

In Eggdrop v1.8, Eggdrop bots would automatically attempt to upgrade any
botnet link to an SSL/TLS connection. Since v1.9, the user is required
to explicitly request an SSL/TLS connection by prefixing the port with a
'+'. If you wish your botnet to take advantage of encryption, use the
.chaddr command to update your ports to start with a '+'.

Tcl Commands

A lot of backwards-compatible additions and changes have been made to
Tcl commands. Please look at doc/tcl-commands.doc to see them.

Documentation

Documentation has been updated to reflect new and removed commands and
variables, and to cover the new TOML configuration format.
